\n| title = Ilsa, She Wolf of the SS\n| journal = The Independent Film Journal\n| volume = 76 | issue = 6 | date = 1975-08-20\n| doi = <!-- ??.????/?????????? -->\n| url = <!-- ????://??????.????/?????? -->\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"kehr\">{{cite news \n| last = Kehr | first = David\n| url = http://www.chicagoreader.com/chicago/Film?oid=1052810 \n| title = Ilsa, She-Wolf of the SS\n| work = Chicago Reader | date = 2009-05-09\n| access-date = 2020-03-01\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200301150838/https://www.chicagoreader.com/chicago/Film?oid=1052810\n| archive-date = 2020-03-01 | url-status = live\n}}</ref>\n\n<!-- probably not notable\n<ref name=\"metal\">{{cite web \n| url = http://www.metal-archives.com/albums/At_War/Ordered_to_Kill/9086 \n| title = Album \"Ordered to Kill\" by At War \n| work = Encyclopaedia Metallum \n| access-date = 2020-03-01 \n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190426091839/http://www.metal-archives.com/albums/At_War/Ordered_to_Kill/9086\n| archive-date = 2019-04-26 | url-status = live\n}}</ref> -->\n\n<ref name=\"nyt-obit\">{{cite news\n| last = Genzlinger | first = Neil\n| url = https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/13/movies/dyanne-thorne-dead.html\n| title = Dyanne Thorne, 83, Star of Scandalous \u2018Ilsa\u2019 Films, Is Dead\n| work = [[The New York Times]]\n| date = 2020-02-13\n| access-date = 2020-03-01\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200221101433/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/13/movies/dyanne-thorne-dead.html\n| archive-date = 2020-02-21 | url-status = live\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"porning\">{{cite book \n| last1 = Sarracino | first1 = Carmine\n| last2 = Scott | first2 = Kevin M.\n| title = The Porning Of America: The Rise Of Porn Culture, What It Means, And Where We Go From Here\n| url = https://archive.org/details/porningofamerica0000sarr\n| url-access = registration | location = Boston | publisher = Beacon Press | year = 2008\n| isbn = 978-0-8070-6153-4\n| page = [https://archive.org/details/porningofamerica0000sarr/page/78 78]\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"rotten\">{{Rotten Tomatoes|ilsa_she_wolf_of_the_ss|Ilsa, She Wolf of the SS}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"siskel\">{{cite news \n| last = Siskel | first = Gene | author-link = Gene Siskel\n| date = 1975-08-14\n| url = https://www.newspapers.com/clip/37541383/ \n| title = Two 'shlockers' a waste of time \n| work = [[Chicago Tribune]]\n| page = 32\n| access-date = 2020-03-01\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200301145320/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/37541383/gene-siskel-movie-reviewsilsa-she/\n| archive-date = 2020-03-01 | url-status = live\n}}</ref>\n\n<!-- title appears badly garbled, cannot locate this\n<ref name=\"variety\">{{cite journal |date=January 22, 1975 |title='Express' Sock 42\u00bdG, Hub; 'Ilsa' Lush 18G, 'G'father II' 28\u00bdG, 5th |url= |journal=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |page=21}}</ref> \n-->\n\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0071650|Ilsa, She Wolf of the SS}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|ilsa_she_wolf_of_the_ss|Ilsa, She Wolf of the SS}}\n\n{{Ilsa}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ilsa She Wolf Of The SS}}\n[[Category:1975 films]]\n[[Category:1975 horror films]]\n[[Category:1970s war films]]\n[[Category:Canadian films]]\n[[Category:Canadian war films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films based on actual events]]\n[[Category:Films about Nazi Germany]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Los Angeles County]]\n[[Category:Nazi exploitation films]]\n[[Category:Obscenity controversies in film]]\n[[Category:Sexploitation films]]\n[[Category:Canadian splatter films]]\n[[Category:Fictional Nazis]]\n[[Category:Fictional German people]]\n[[Category:Female characters in film]]\n[[Category:1970s exploitation films]]\n", "name_user": "Da\u00df W\u00f6lf", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAnalysis:nothing wrong here but could use attribution to a source", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ilsa,_She_Wolf_of_the_SS"}
{"title_page": "Religion in Ethiopia", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Pie chart\n|thumb = right\n|caption = Religion in Ethiopia (2007)<ref name=Religion-2007>[https://web.archive.org/web/20120604045256/http://www.csa.gov.et/pdf/Cen2007_firstdraft.pdf 2007 Ethiopian census, first draft], Ethiopian Central Statistical Agency (accessed 6 May 2009)</ref>\n\n|label1 = [[Ethiopian Orthodox Church|Ethiopian Orthodoxy]]\n|value1 = 43.5\n|color1 = Orchid\n|label2 = [[Islam in Ethiopia|Islam]]\n|value2 = 33.9\n|color2 = Green\n|label3 = [[Pentay]] ([[P'ent'ay (Ethiopian Evangelicalism)|Protestantism]])\n|value3 = 18.6\n|color3 = DodgerBlue\n|label4 = [[Traditional African religion|Traditional faiths]]\n|value4 = 2.6\n|color4 = GreenYellow\n|label5 = [[Catholic Church in Ethiopia|Roman Catholicism]]\n|value5 = 0.7\n|color5 = Yellow\n|label6 = Others\n|value6 = 0.7\n|color6 = Red\n}}\n\n[[File:Panoramic View of the Holy Trinity Cathedral, Addis Ababa, Ethiopia (3435906326).jpg|thumb|[[Holy Trinity Cathedral (Addis Ababa)|Holy Trinity Cathedral]] in [[Addis Ababa]]. [[Ethiopia]] was one of the first regions in the world to adopt [[Christianity]].]]\n'''Religion in Ethiopia''' consists of a number of faiths. Among these mainly [[Abrahamic religion]]s, the most numerous is [[Christianity]] ([[Ethiopian Orthodox Church|Ethiopian Orthodoxy]], [[Pentay]], [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholic]]) totaling at 62.8%, followed by [[Islam]] at 33.9% . There is also a longstanding but small [[Beta Israel|Jewish]] community. Some adherents of the [[Bah\u00e1'\u00ed Faith]] likewise exist in a number of urban and rural areas. Additionally, there are a few followers of [[Traditional African religion|traditional faiths]], who mainly reside in the southwestern part of the country.\n\nAccording to the national census conducted in 2007, over 32 million people or 43.5% were reported to be [[Ethiopian Orthodox Christianity|Ethiopian Orthodox Christians]], over 25 million or 33.9% were reported to be [[Islam in Ethiopia|Muslim]], 13,7 million, or 18.6%, were [[P'ent'ay|Protestants]], and just under two million or 2.6% adhered to traditional beliefs.<ref name=Religion-2007>[https://web.archive.org/web/20120604045256/http://www.csa.gov.et/pdf/Cen2007_firstdraft.pdf 2007 Ethiopian census, first draft], Ethiopian Central Statistical Agency (accessed 6 May 2009)</ref> Neither in the 2007 census, nor in the 1994 census, were responses reported in further detail: for example, those who identified themselves as Hindus, Jewish, Baha'i, agnostics or atheists were counted as \"Other\".\n\nThe [[Kingdom of Aksum]] in present-day [[Ethiopia]] and [[Eritrea]] was one of the first Christian countries in the world, having officially adopted [[Christianity]] as the state religion in the 4th century.<ref>S. C. Munro-Hay, ''Aksum: An African Civilization of Late Antiquity'' (Edinburgh: University Press, 1991), p. 77. {{ISBN|0-7486-0106-6}}</ref> Ethiopia was the only region of [[Africa]] to survive the expansion of Islam as a Christian state.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.historyworld.net/wrldhis/PlainTextHistories.asp?historyid=ab92|title=HISTORY OF ETHIOPIA|work=historyworld.net}}</ref>\n\n== Geography ==\nIn general, most of the [[Christianity in Ethiopia|Christians]] (largely members of the [[Oriental Orthodox|non-Chalcedonian]] [[Ethiopian Orthodox Tewahedo Church]]) live in the highlands, while [[Islam|Muslims]] and adherents of traditional African religions tend to inhabit more lowland regions in the east and south of the country.{{citation needed|date=May 2016}} The numerous indigenous [[African religions]] in Ethiopia operate mainly in the far southwest and western borderlands.\n\n==Abrahamic religions==\n[[File:Jimmamosque.jpg|thumb|upright|A [[mosque]] in [[Jimma]].]]\n[[File:ET Addis asv2018-01 img16 Entoto.jpg|thumb|left|upright|A [[Church (building)|church]] in [[Addis Ababa]].]]\nEthiopia has close historical ties to all three of the world's major [[Abrahamic religions]]. Christians form the majority of the population.<ref name=\"CIA\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/et.html |title=CIA \u2013 The World Factbook \u2013 Ethiopia |publisher=Cia.gov |accessdate=16 March 2009}}</ref> Islam is the second most followed religion, with 33.9% of the population being adherents. 2.6% of the population (mainly in the far south and southwest) follow traditional religions; other religions ([[Bah\u00e1'\u00ed Faith|Bah\u00e1'\u00ed]], [[Beta Israel|Judaism]], etc.) make up the remaining 0.6%.<ref name=\"Religion-2007\"/> Ethiopia is the site of the first [[Hijra (Islam)|hijra]] in Islamic history and the oldest Muslim settlement in Africa at [[Negash]]. Until the 1980s, a substantial population of [[Ethiopian Jews]] resided in Ethiopia. The country is also the spiritual homeland of the [[Rastafari movement|Rastafari religious movement]].\n\n===Christianity===\n{{main|Christianity in Ethiopia}}\n[[File:Ark of the Covenant church in Axum Ethiopia.jpg|thumb|right|150px|The [[Church of Our Lady Mary of Zion]], rumored to hold the original [[Ark of the Covenant]]]]\nEthiopia is one of the oldest Christian states in the world. The [[Ethiopian Orthodox Church]] is an [[Oriental Orthodox Church]], which is the largest Christian denomination in Ethiopia. It was part of the [[Coptic Orthodox Church]] until 1959, and is the only pre-colonial Orthodox church in [[Sub-Saharan Africa]]. The apostle [[Saint Matthew|St. Matthew]] is said to have died in Ethiopia.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/10056b.htm | title=CATHOLIC ENCYCLOPEDIA: St. Matthew}}</ref>\n[[File:Bete Giyorgis 03.jpg|thumb|left|The rock-hewn [[Church of Saint George, Lalibela|Church of Saint George]] in [[Lalibela]] is a [[World Heritage Site|UNESCO World Heritage Site]].]]\nAccording to the government's 1994 census (which the [[CIA World Factbook]] follows), 61.6% of the Ethiopian population was Christian: 50.6% of the total were [[Ethiopian Orthodox]], 10.1% were various [[P'ent'ay (Ethiopian Evangelicalism)|Protestant]] denominations (such as [[P'ent'ay]] and the [[Lutheranism|Lutheran]] [[Ethiopian Evangelical Church Mekane Yesus]]), and [[Ethiopian Catholic Church|Roman Catholics]] constituted 0.9% of the population).<ref name=Religion-1994>[http://www.csa.gov.et/surveys/Population%20and%20Housing%20Census%201994/survey0/index.html \"Population and Housing Census of 1994: Religion\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081207032949/http://www.csa.gov.et/surveys/Population%20and%20Housing%20Census%201994/survey0/index.html |date=7 December 2008 }} (accessed 6 May 2009)</ref> The U.S. State Department estimates that just over 50% of the country is Christian (40 to 45% of the population belongs to the Ethiopian Orthodox Church, about 10% are members of Christian evangelical and Pentecostal groups).<ref name=\"Ethiopia\">[https://2001-2009.state.gov/g/drl/rls/irf/2007/90097.htm Ethiopia: International Religious Freedom Report, 2007] U.S. State Department (accessed 6 May 2009)</ref><ref>[https://2001-2009.state.gov/g/drl/rls/irf/2006/71301.htm Ethiopia: International Religious Freedom Report 2006] U.S. State Department (accessed 6 May 2009)</ref> Orthodox Ethiopian Christians are predominant in the [[Tigray Region|Tigray]] (95.6%) and [[Amhara Region|Amhara]] (82.5%), while the majority of Protestants live in the [[Southern Nations, Nationalities and Peoples Region]] or SNNPR (55.5% of the inhabitants) and the [[Oromia Region]] (4.8 million or 17.7%).<ref name=Religion-2007/> According to the government's most recent census from 2007, Christians constitute 62.8% of the total population, with the largest group being [[Ethiopian Orthodox]] Christians at 43.5%, followed by [[P'ent'ay (Ethiopian Evangelicalism)|Protestants]] 18.6% and [[Roman Catholicism in Ethiopia|Catholics]] at 0.7%.<ref name=\"Religion-2007\"/> A 2015 study estimates some 400,000 Christian believers from a Muslim background in the country, most of them belonging to some form of Protestantism.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Johnstone|first1=Patrick|last2=Miller|first2=Duane|title=Believers in Christ from a Muslim Background: A Global Census|journal=IJRR|date=2015|volume=11|page=14|url=https://www.academia.edu/16338087}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Ethiopian Painting 2005 SeanMcClean.JPG|right|thumb|A leather painting depicting [[Ethiopian Orthodox Tewahedo Church|Ethiopian Orthodox]] priests playing [[sistrum|sistra]] and a [[drum]].]]\nThe [[Kingdom of Aksum]] was one of the first nations to officially accept [[Christianity]], when St. [[Saint Frumentius|Frumentius]] of [[Tyre (Lebanon)|Tyre]], called Fremnatos or Abba Selama (\"Father of Peace\") in Ethiopia, converted King [[Ezana of Axum|Ezana]] during the 4th century [[Anno Domini|AD]]. Many believe that the Gospel had entered Ethiopia even earlier, with the royal official described as being baptised by [[Philip the Evangelist]] in chapter eight of the [[Acts of the Apostles]] (Acts 8:26\u201339). Orthodox Christianity has a long history in Ethiopia dating back to the 1st century, and is dominant in northern and central Ethiopia. Both Orthodox and Protestant Christianity have large representations in southern and western Ethiopia. A small ancient group of [[Jews]], the [[Beta Israel]], live in northwestern Ethiopia, though most emigrated to [[Israel]] in the last decades of the 20th century as part of the rescue missions undertaken by the Israeli government, [[Operation Moses]] and [[Operation Solomon]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/Judaism/ejhist.html |title=The History of Ethiopian Jews |publisher=Jewishvirtuallibrary.org |accessdate=16 March 2009}}</ref> Some Israeli and Jewish scholars consider these Ethiopian Jews as a historical ''[[Lost Tribe of Israel]]''. Today, the [[Ethiopian Orthodox Tewahedo Church]], part of [[Oriental Orthodoxy]], is by far the largest denomination, though a number of [[P'ent'ay (Ethiopian Evangelicalism)|Protestants]] ([[P'ent'ay]]) churches have recently gained ground. Since the 18th century there has existed a relatively small ([[uniate]]) [[Ethiopian Catholic Church]] in [[full communion]] with [[Rome]], with adherents making up less than 1% of the total population.<ref name=\"Religion-2007\"/>\n\nThe name \"Ethiopia\" (Hebrew ''Kush'') is mentioned in the Bible numerous times (thirty-seven times in the [[Authorised Version|King James version]]). Abyssinia is also mentioned in the [[Qur'an]] and [[Hadith]]. While many Ethiopians claim that the Bible references of Kush apply to their own ancient civilization, pointing out that the [[Gihon]] river, a name for the [[Nile]], is said to flow through the land, some scholars believe that the use of the term referred to the [[Kingdom of Kush]] in particular, or Africa outside of Egypt in general. The modern name ''Ethiopia'' is from the [[Greek language|Greek]] term ''[[Aethiopia]]'' used to translate ''Kush'', and was applied to all of Sub-Saharan Africa, including what is now [[Sudan]], but with a few classical geographers giving more detailed descriptions of present-day Ethiopia and Eritrea (e.g. [[Adulis]]) as well.\n\n===Islam===\n{{main|Islam in Ethiopia}}\n[[File:ET Mekele asv2018-01 img33 Mosque.jpg|thumb|right|A [[mosque]] in [[Mekelle]].]]\n[[Islam in Ethiopia]] dates back to the founding of the religion; in 615, when a group of Muslims were counseled by Muhammad to escape persecution in [[Mecca]] and [[Migration to Abyssinia|travel to Ethiopia via modern-day Eritrea]], which was ruled by [[Ashama ibn Abjar]], a pious Christian king. [[Bilal ibn Ribah]], the first [[Muezzin]], the person chosen to call the faithful to prayer, and one of the foremost companions of Muhammad, was born in Mecca to an Abyssinian mother. Moreover, the largest portion of [[non-Arab Companions of Muhammad]] belonged to Ethiopian ethnic groups.\n\nAccording to the most recent 2007 [[Central Statistical Agency (Ethiopia)|CSA]] governmental data, Muslims are 33.9% of the population,<ref name=\"Religion-2007\"/> up from 32.8% in 1994 (according to the census data of that year).<ref name=Religion-1994/><ref>[https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/et.html#People CIA Factbook \u2013 Ethiopia]</ref>\nBefore the publication of the 2007 census results, however, the U.S. State Department estimated that \"approximately 45 percent of the population is Sunni Muslim.\"<ref name=\"Ethiopia\"/><ref>[https://2009-2017.state.gov/r/pa/ei/bgn/2859.htm Ethiopia (03/08)<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Roughly 68% of Ethiopian Muslims are Sunni, whilst 23% are [[non-denominational Muslim]]s,<ref>https://www.pewforum.org/2012/08/09/the-worlds-muslims-unity-and-diversity-1-religious-affiliation/#identity</ref> some belonging to various [[Sufi]] orders. Islam first arrived in Ethiopia in 614 with the [[Migration to Abyssinia|First Migration to Abyssinia]]. [[Addis Ababa]], Ethiopia's capital city, is home to about 443,821 Muslims or 16.2%.<ref>Summary and Statistical Report of the 2007 Population and Housing Census Results. [ONLINE] Available at: https://web.archive.org/web/20090305231227/http://www.csa.gov.et/pdf/Cen2007_firstdraft.pdf. [Accessed 19 January 2017]</ref> While Muslims can be found in almost every community, Islam is most prevalent in the [[Somali Region|Somali]] (98.4%), [[Afar Region|Afar]] (95.3%) and [[Oromia Region|Oromia]] (47.5%) Regions.<ref name=Religion-2007/> Haile Selassie's government reportedly concealed the actual figures of the Muslim population in order to present Ethiopia as a Christian nation to the outside world.<ref>{{cite book|authorlink=Nehemia Levtzion |last1=Levtzion |first1=Nehemia |title=The History of Islam in Africa |publisher=Ohio University Press |page=240-241 |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=J1Ipt5A9mLMC&pg=PA240&lpg=PA240&dq=Haile+selassie%27s+regime+which+had+presented+Ethiopia+abroad+as+a+christian+country,+had+carefully+kepy+two+secrets&source=bl&ots=huCcdZSf1Q&sig=ACfU3U1vqLYtrIocd_kK0sBiwViThe3fvA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjx4Oe-nqvnAhUTmHIEHX3pD5wQ6AEwAHoECAsQAQ#v=onepage&q=Haile%20selassie's%20regime%20which%20had%20presented%20Ethiopia%20abroad%20as%20a%20christian%20country%2C%20had%20carefully%20kepy%20two%20secrets&f=false}}</ref> The writers of ''Ethiopia: a country study'' claimed that Islam made up 50% of the total population in 1991 based on the 1984 census commissioned by the [[Derg]] regime.<ref>{{cite book|authorlink=Nehemia Levtzion |last1=Levtzion |first1=Nehemia |title=The History of Islam in Africa |publisher=Ohio University Press |page=240-241 |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=J1Ipt5A9mLMC&pg=PA240&lpg=PA240&dq=Haile+selassie%27s+regime+which+had+presented+Ethiopia+abroad+as+a+christian+country,+had+carefully+kepy+two+secrets&source=bl&ots=huCcdZSf1Q&sig=ACfU3U1vqLYtrIocd_kK0sBiwViThe3fvA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjx4Oe-nqvnAhUTmHIEHX3pD5wQ6AEwAHoECAsQAQ#v=onepage&q=Haile%20selassie's%20regime%20which%20had%20presented%20Ethiopia%20abroad%20as%20a%20christian%20country%2C%20had%20carefully%20kepy%20two%20secrets&f=false}}</ref> Some web columnist even say the Muslim population are the majority and disagree with the current Ethiopian governments claims.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Prunier |first1=G\u00e9rard |title=Understanding Contemporary Ethiopia: Monarchy, Revolution and the Legacy of Meles Zenawi |publisher=Oxford University Press |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=wnxeCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT100&dq=muslims+could+make+up+majority+ethiopia&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiTnJXoq6vnAhWQhXIEHZpDBKYQ6AEIKTAA#v=onepage&q=muslims%20could%20make%20up%20majority%20ethiopia&f=false}}</ref>\n\n===Judaism===\n{{main|Beta Israel}}\n[[File:Ethiopie-falasha.jpg|thumb|right|Areas inhabited by the [[Beta Israel]] before their mass aliyah.]]\nThe [[Beta Israel]], also known as the ''Falashas'' (though this term is considered derogatory), are a long-isolated group of [[African Jews]] who have lived in Ethiopia since antiquity. Their existence was not widely known to the outside world for many years, and they likewise were not aware of other Jewish groups outside of their own community.<ref>Mark Shapiro, [http://www.kulanu.org/ethiopia/return-lost-tribe.php \"Return of a Lost Tribe\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090106162300/http://www.kulanu.org/ethiopia/return-lost-tribe.php |date=6 January 2009 }}</ref> They became known to [[Western world|the West]] during the 19th and 20th centuries, and were accepted as Jews by the [[Israel]]i government in 1975. After this, [[Operation Moses]] and [[Operation Solomon]], conducted in 1984 and 1991, respectively, airlifted the vast majority of the Ethiopian Jewish population to Israel, where there is currently a population of 150,000 Beta Israel. A small Jewish community still exists in Ethiopia, although it is mostly composed of [[Falash Mura]], Ethiopian Jews who converted to Christianity in the past, and as such have not been recognized as Jews by the State of Israel, but have returned to Judaism (the Falash Mura now number some 22,000).\n\n===Bah\u00e1'\u00ed faith===\n{{main|Bah\u00e1'\u00ed Faith in Ethiopia}}\nThe [[Bah\u00e1'\u00ed Faith]] in Ethiopia begins after [[`Abdu'l-Bah\u00e1]] wrote letters encouraging taking the religion to Africa in 1916.<ref name=\"ToDP8\">{{cite book |author = `Abdu'l-Bah\u00e1 |authorlink = `Abdu'l-Bah\u00e1 | origyear = 1916\u201317 |year = 1991 |title = Tablets of the Divine Plan |edition = Paperback |publisher = Bah\u00e1'\u00ed Publishing Trust |location = Wilmette, IL |isbn = 0-87743-233-3 |url =http://reference.bahai.org/en/t/ab/TDP/tdp-8.html.iso8859-1 | pages = 47\u201359}}</ref> Mr. Sabri Elais, then a 27-year-old Bah\u00e1'\u00ed from Alexandria, Egypt, introduced the Bah\u00e1'\u00ed Faith to Ethiopia in 1933.<ref>Hassan, Gamal (2008). Moths Turned Eagles, Addis Ababa, Ethiopia; The National Spiritual Assembly of the Bah\u00e1'\u00eds of Ethiopia.</ref> A year later, in November 1934, the first Bah\u00e1'\u00ed [[Local Spiritual Assembly]] of the country was formed in [[Addis Ababa]].<ref name=\"info\">{{cite web| last = Hassall | first = Graham | title = Ethiopia | work = Research notes | publisher = Asia Pacific Bah\u00e1'\u00ed Studies | url = http://bahai-library.com/asia-pacific/country%20files/ethiopia.htm | accessdate = 21 December 2008}}</ref> In 1962, Ethiopia Bah\u00e1'\u00eds had elected a [[National Spiritual Assembly]].<ref name=\"telegram\">{{cite book  |editor-last= Rabbani |editor-first=Ruhiyyih |editor-link=R\u00fah\u00edyyih Khanum |year= 1992 |title= The Ministry of the Custodians 1957\u20131963 |publisher= Bah\u00e1'\u00ed World Centre |page = 398 |isbn= 0-85398-350-X |url= http://bahai-library.com/uhj_ministry_custodians }}</ref> By 1963, there were seven localities with smaller groups of Bah\u00e1'\u00eds in the country.<ref name=\"stats\">{{cite web | url =http://bahai-library.com/handscause_statistics_1953-63&chapter=1 | title = The Bah\u00e1'\u00ed Faith: 1844\u20131963: Information Statistical and Comparative, Including the Achievements of the Ten Year International Bah\u00e1'\u00ed Teaching & Consolidation Plan 1953\u20131963| author = Compiled by [[Hands of the Cause]] Residing in the Holy Land | pages = 28, 55}}</ref> The [[Association of Religion Data Archives]] estimated that there were around 27,000 Bah\u00e1'\u00ed adherents in 2005.<ref name=\"WCE-05\">{{cite web| title = Most Baha'i Nations (2005) | work = QuickLists > Compare Nations > Religions > | publisher = The Association of Religion Data Archives | year = 2005| url =http://www.thearda.com/QuickLists/QuickList_40c.asp | accessdate = 4 July 2009}}</ref> The Ethiopian community celebrated its diamond jubile in January 2009.<ref name=\"program\">{{cite web   |author=multiple   | title = North American Bah\u00e1'\u00ed Choir in Ethiopia 2009   | date = January 2009   | url = https://docs.google.com/Doc?id=dgshgd2h_760cf9jvwgs&hl=en   | accessdate = 30 August 2009}}</ref> {{As of | 2016}} the largest Bah\u00e1'\u00ed community is in Addis Ababa.<ref>\n{{cite web\n|url=http://news.bahai.org/story/486 \n|title=Families and youth identified as keys to reducing poverty \n|publisher=News.bahai.org |accessdate=16 March 2009\n}}\n</ref>\nA number of towns (such as Awassa, Nazareth, Mekele, Zway and Shashemenie) and rural areas in Oromia and the Southern Nations, Nationalities, and People's Region (SNNPR) have active and growing Bah\u00e1'\u00ed communities.{{citation needed|date=May 2016}}\n\n==Traditional faiths==\n{{See also|Waaq}}\nAn estimated 2.6% of Ethiopia's population adheres to various [[Traditional African religion|traditional faiths]], according to the 2007 census (down from 4.6% in the 1994 census data). The largest numbers of practitioners of traditional religions are in the SNNPR (about 993,000 people) and Oromia (895,000).<ref name=Religion-2007/>\n\n==Views on the emperors==\nEthiopia is the spiritual homeland of the [[Rastafari movement]], whose adherents believe Ethiopia is [[Zion]]. The Rastafari view Emperor [[Haile Selassie]] as [[Jesus]], the human incarnation of God. The Emperor himself was the defender of the Ethiopian Orthodox Church, that also has a concept of Zion, {{Citation needed span|date=February 2015|1=although it represents a unique and complex concept, referring figuratively to St. [[Blessed Virgin Mary|Mary]], but also to Ethiopia as a bastion of Christianity surrounded by Muslims and other religions, much like [[Mount Zion]] in the Bible}}. It is also used to refer to [[Axum]], the ancient capital and religious centre of Ethiopian Orthodox Christians, or to its primary church, called [[Church of Our Lady Mary of Zion]].<ref>Taddesse Tamrat, ''Church and State''.</ref>{{Full citation needed|date=February 2015}}\n\n==Religious politics and tensions==\n[[Freedom of religion]] is provided by the [[1995 Constitution of Ethiopia|constitution of 1995]], and freedom of worship had also been guaranteed by the 1930 and 1955 Constitutions of Ethiopia, although in certain localities this principle is not always respected in practice. There is no state religion, and it is forbidden to form political parties based upon religion; all religious groups are required to register with the government, and renew their registration once every three years. It is a crime in Ethiopia to incite one religion against another. Discrimination against Muslims have been rampant since the creation of modern Ethiopia, Muslims were marginalized in the Haile Selassie era.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Loimeier |first1=Roman |title=Islamic Reform in Twentieth-Century Africa |publisher=Edinburgh University Press |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=IDZYDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT238&lpg=PT238&dq=haile+selassie+second+class+citizens+muslim&source=bl&ots=Y_l_S7k9P7&sig=ACfU3U3XdxA1LkZ1IGFZpq-EqImrbZcaTA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjCgc6Og4_oAhUsT98KHcqBDJEQ6AEwBHoECAwQAQ#v=onepage&q=haile%20selassie%20second%20class%20citizens%20muslim&f=false}}</ref> Haile Selassie actually came to power during the rise of opposition to Muslims in government positions.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Knight |first1=Michael |title=Journey to the End of Islam |publisher=Soft Skull Press |page=160 |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=9XM4AAAAQBAJ&pg=PA160&dq=haile+selassie+anti+muslim&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiJt_LMg4_oAhVOnOAKHbqTA_IQ6AEIXDAG#v=onepage&q=haile%20selassie%20anti%20muslim&f=false}}</ref> U.S ambassador [[David H. Shinn]] stated in 2005 that the Ethiopian leadership continued to be largely Christian.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Angore |first1=T |title=Reconstruction of Ethiopia's Collective Memory by Rewriting its History |publisher=Tilburg University |page=103 |url=https://pure.uvt.nl/ws/portalfiles/portal/20054442/Angore_Reconstructing_04_12_2017_emb_tot_04_12_2018.pdf}}</ref> Tension between Christian and Muslim Oromo were witnessed during the [[2005 Ethiopian general election]], when Muslim [[Arsi Oromo]] denounced the [[Shewa]] Oromo for participating in political nepotism.<ref>{{cite book |title=Contested Power in Ethiopia: Traditional Authorities and Multi-Party Elections |publisher=BRILL |page=189 |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=ecIyAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA189&dq=opdo+christian+oromo&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj3-NLp2ZnoAhVPmuAKHXCxCVwQ6AEIOjAC#v=onepage&q=opdo%20christian%20oromo&f=false}}</ref> There is some tension between members of the Ethiopian Orthodox Church and Protestant Christians, as well as between the Ethiopian Orthodox and Muslims in general. According to the [[Barnabas Fund]], 55 churches were torched in March 2011 in the [[Jimma Zone]] by Muslims after a dispute. In December 2019 several mosques and Muslim owned businesses were attacked in the Christian dominated [[Amhara Region]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Five arrested for attack on mosques in Ethiopia's Amhara region |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/12/arrested-attack-mosques-ethiopia-amhara-region-191221194353132.html |agency=Al Jazeera}}</ref>\n\n=== Orthodox Christian-Muslim Relations ===\nIn the [[Hadith]], Prophet Mohammed explicitly prohibited jihad against the Abyssinians as long as they were not hostile to Muslims.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Ghunaimi |first1=Mohammad |title=The Muslim Conception of International Law and the Western Approach |publisher=Springer Science & Business Media |page=203 |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=toQJBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA203&dq=leave+the+abyssinians&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi4hu2x1szoAhWBiOAKHV1JB48Q6AEISzAE#v=onepage&q=leave%20the%20abyssinians&f=false}}</ref> This is because Abyssinia\u2019s (present-day Ethiopia) Aksumite monarch embraced a group of Muslims embarking on the first Hijrah from Arabia, fleeing persecution from their homeland.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Budge|first=E. A. Wallis|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KWQtBAAAQBAJ&lpg=PR7&pg=PR7#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=A History of Ethiopia: Volume I (Routledge Revivals): Nubia and Abyssinia|date=2014-08-01|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-317-64915-1|language=en}}</ref> The founder of [[Solomonic dynasty]], [[Yekuno Amlak]] was heavily assisted by Muslim [[Sultanate of Showa]] in his struggle against the [[Zagwe dynasty]].<ref>{{cite book |title=Oromo of Ethiopia with special emphasis on the Gibe region |page=4 |url=https://eprints.soas.ac.uk/29226/1/10731321.pdf}}</ref> Yekuno Amlak paid back this favor when the Sultan of Shewa appealed to him to put down a insurrection in Showa.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Selassie |first1=Sergew |title=Ancient and Medieval Ethiopian History to 1270 |page=290 |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=c91yAAAAMAAJ&dq=according+to+dil+gamis&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=dil+gamis}}</ref> These friendly and collaborative relations between Muslim and Christian states would soon deteriorate in the following centuries. In the early fourteenth century Emperor [[Amda Seyon]] launched a crusade against the neighboring Muslim state of [[Ifat Sultanate]], several mosques were demolished.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Budge |first1=E.A |title=A History of Ethiopia: Volume I (Routledge Revivals): Nubia and Abyssinia |publisher=Routledge |page=297 |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=KWQtBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA297&dq=amda+seyon+mosques&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj50_aV3MzoAhXvmOAKHciGDHwQ6AEIMDAB#v=onepage&q=amda%20seyon%20mosques&f=false}}</ref> In the early fifteenth century Emperor [[Zara Yaqob]] invaded the Muslim state of [[Hadiya Sultanate]] and married the captured Hadiya princess [[Eleni]] which was condemned by Muslims.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hassen |first1=Mohammed |title=Oromo of Ethiopia with special emphasis on the Gibe region |publisher=University of London |page=22 |url=https://eprints.soas.ac.uk/29226/1/10731321.pdf}}</ref> In the late fifteenth century [[Adal Sultanate]] invaded Abyssinia led by Imam [[Mahfuz]], his defeat brought about the early 16th century [[Abyssinian\u2013Adal war|Jihad]] of the [[Adal Sultanate|Adal]]ese [[Imam]] [[Ahmed Gran]] against Ethiopia, where several churches were demolished.<ref>{{cite web |title=Adal |url=https://www.britannica.com/place/Adal |website=Encylopedia Britannica}}</ref>\n\n==Adherents==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! '''[[Christianity in Ethiopia|Christians]]'''\n! ''[[Ethiopian Orthodox Church|Ethiopian Orthodox]]''\n! ''[[P'ent'ay|Protestants]]''\n! ''[[Ethiopian Catholic Church|Catholics]]''\n! '''[[Islam in Ethiopia|Muslims]]'''\n! '''[[Traditional African religion|Traditional faiths]]'''\n! '''Other'''\n|-\n| 1994\n| '''61.6%'''\n| 50.6%\n| 10.1%\n| 0.9%\n| '''32.8%'''\n| '''4.6%'''\n| '''1.0%'''\n|-\n| 2007\n| '''62.8%'''\n| 43.5%\n| 18.6%\n| 0.7%\n| '''33.9%'''\n| '''2.6%'''\n| '''0.7%'''\n|-\n| ''Growth''\n| ''1.2%''\n| ''-7.1%''\n| ''8.5%''\n| ''-0.2%''\n| ''1.1%''\n| ''-2.0%''\n| ''-0.3%''\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! '''[[Christianity in Ethiopia|Christians]]'''\n! ''[[Ethiopian Orthodox Church|Ethiopian Orthodox]]''\n! ''[[P'ent'ay|Protestants]]''\n! ''[[Ethiopian Catholic Church|Catholics]]''\n! '''[[Islam in Ethiopia|Muslims]]'''\n! '''[[Traditional African religion|Traditional faiths]]'''\n! '''Other'''\n|-\n| 1994\n| '''32,689,482'''\n| 26,844,932\n| 5,366,360\n| 478,190\n| '''17,406,087'''\n| '''2,444,085'''\n| '''531,323'''\n|-\n| 2007\n| '''46,420,822'''\n| 32,154,550\n| 13,748,842\n| 517,430\n| '''25,058,373'''\n| '''1,921,881'''\n| '''517,430'''\n|-\n| ''Growth''\n| ''13,731,340''\n| ''5,309,618''\n| ''8,382,482''\n| ''39,240''\n| ''7,652,286''\n| ''-522,204''\n| ''-13,893''\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! align=center colspan=1|\n! align=center colspan=1| 1994\n! align=center colspan=1| 2007\n! align=center colspan=1| 1994\n! align=center colspan=1| 2007\n! align=center colspan=1| 1994\n! align=center colspan=1| 2007\n! align=center colspan=1| 1994\n! align=center colspan=1| 2007\n! align=center colspan=1| 1994\n! align=center colspan=1| 2007\n! align=center colspan=1| 1994\n! 